3. Phase-by-Phase Implementation Plan
Phase 1: Core API & Safety Gateway (Safety First)
Goal: Every query entering the system is immediately classified and dangerous intents
are short-circuited, before any expensive retrieval.
3.1 API Contract (Frontend ↔ Backend)
Use the updated API contract from HealthyLabs_inference.pdf, page 8:
json
POST /v1/chat
{
 "query_text": "...",
 "session_id": "...",
 "patient_context": { // optional
 "age": 65,
 "gender": "male",
 "current_medications": [...],
 "known_conditions": [...],
 "allergies": [...]
 },
 "chat_history": []
}
Implementation tasks:
Create api/request_models.py with Pydantic models for this exact schema.
Create api/routes.py: a single endpoint that extracts the payload and passes it
to the orchestrator.
Return a structured response including answer, citations, strategy_used, and
contradictions_found (see page 7).
3.2 Intent Guard (orchestrator/intent_guard.py)
Every query must be classified before any retrieval.
Use a fast, lightweight LLM call (e.g., GPT-3.5 or a fine-tuned small model) with a
strict prompt.
Classes: Emergency/Diagnostic, Research, Educational.
Emergency override: If Emergency is detected, return immediately a
hardcoded disclaimer message (e.g., “This is not a substitute for professional
medical advice. If you are experiencing a medical emergency, please call your
local emergency services immediately.”) and do not proceed further. This
implements the safety bypass from the Inference document (page 4).
Phase 2: The Self-RAG Brain (Orchestrator)
This is the controller that decides what retrieval strategies to run, based on query
characteristics. It directly maps to the stepwise approach.pdf steps 2-6 and the RAG
model approach.pdf.
3.3 Self-RAG Router (orchestrator/self_rag_router.py)
Input: query_text, patient_context (to enrich the decision), chat_history.
LLM Decision Prompt: Craft a prompt that outputs a JSON decision:
json
{
 "strategy": "direct" | "hyde" | "multi_query" | "decompose",
 "reason": "string",
 "sub_queries": [...] // used by decompose/multi_query
}
Rules (derived from your discussions):
Vague query (e.g., “I feel tired after my treatment”) → hyde
Multiple interpretations (e.g., “What are the risks of pneumonia?” could be
about disease or treatment) → multi_query
Multi-intent / multi-step (e.g., “Headache after pneumonia antibiotics”) →
decompose
Straightforward → direct
Also, if patient_context is present, the router always adds a
knowledge_graph_override flag that will later trigger kg_overrides.py.
Important: The router should be prepared to cascade. For example, it might first try
hyde, and if reflection later signals low confidence, it may then choose multi_query.
This is the iterative loop.
Phase 3: Retrieval Strategies (Data Fetchers)
Implement each strategy as a standalone function. They all call into
retrieval/neo4j_search.py for the final vector search, and
retrieval/kg_overrides.py if the patient is known.
3.4 Vector Search Core (retrieval/neo4j_search.py)
Encapsulate the Cypher query from HealthyLabs_inference.pdf, page 1:
cypher
CALL db.index.vector.queryNodes('atomic_chunk_embedding', $k, $embedding)
YIELD node AS a, score
MATCH (a)-[:PART_OF]->(c:ClinicalContext)-[:CHILD_OF]->(d:Document)
RETURN a.content AS text, a.authority_score AS authority, a.tier AS tier,
 d.doc_uid AS doc_uid, score, c.content AS context_snippet
This returns the top-k AtomicChunks + their parent ClinicalContext snippet +
document identifier.
Use BioLORD-2023 (via HuggingFace or API) to embed the query.
3.5 Direct Retrieval (retrieval/strategies/direct.py)
Embed query_text (optionally enriched with
patient_context.known_conditions as a prompt prefix) and call
neo4j_search.py.
3.6 HYDE (retrieval/strategies/hyde.py)
LLM generates a hypothetical medical document that would answer the query
(semantic expansion).
Embed that hypothetical document and search the vector index with it.
Safety prompt: The HYDE generation must be instructed to produce plausible
but not misleading content, and it is used only for query expansion, never shown
to the user.
3.7 Multi-Query (retrieval/strategies/multi_query.py)
LLM generates several paraphrases of the original query (layman terms, clinical
synonyms, etc.).
Embed each paraphrase, retrieve top-k for each, and pool the results
(deduplicate by document_id + chunk id).
3.8 Decomposition (retrieval/strategies/decompose.py)
LLM splits the query into a sequence of sub-queries (e.g., “causes of headache in
pneumonia recovery” and “antibiotics side effects headache”).
For each sub-query, run direct retrieval (or even further hyde/multi-query for
each).
Aggregate all results, maintaining provenance of which sub-query contributed
which chunks.
3.9 Knowledge Graph Override (retrieval/kg_overrides.py)
Always run if patient_context.current_medications is present.
Use the Cypher example from page 9 of the inference document to check
drug-drug interactions:
cypher
UNWIND $frontend_medications AS current_med
MATCH (d1:Drug {name: $requested_drug})-[:INTERACTS_WITH]->(d2:Drug {name:
current_med.name})
RETURN d1.name, d2.name, r.severity, r.description
If a severe contraindication is found, record it. This will later supersede
vector-based answers: the response builder must give a strict warning.
(Implementation note: The requested_drug is extracted by a quick LLM call on
the query_text, looking for drug names.)
Phase 4: Re-ranking & Aggregation
3.10 Document Pool & Re-ranking
All retrieved chunks from the chosen strategy (or multiple strategies) go into a
single list.
De-duplicate by chunk ID. Keep the highest vector score for each.
Apply a re-ranker: a cross-encoder fine-tuned on medical relevance (e.g.,
BioBERT or MedCPT). Score each (query, chunk) pair and sort.
Authority heuristics: Apply a multiplier based on authority_score (1.0 > 0.7
> 0.3) to bias towards guidelines. The Stepwise approach.pdf suggests
“optionally apply heuristics for authority”.
Trim to the top-N most relevant chunks for the final answer (e.g., keep top 5-7).
Phase 5: Self-RAG Reflection (orchestrator/reflection.py)
Before generating an answer, evaluate the quality of the retrieved pool.
Confidence check: Use an LLM to assess whether the pooled chunks contain
sufficient evidence to answer the query. The prompt returns a confidence score
(0-100%) and a brief reasoning.
Threshold: Set at ≥85% (as per documents). If below, trigger a refinement
loop:
If the original strategy was direct, try hyde.
If hyde was used, try multi_query.
If decompose was used and still low, perhaps flag for human review or ask a
clarifying question back to the user.
Loop Control: Maximum of two extra retrieval passes to control latency and
cost. After that, generate answer anyway but mark confidence as low and
explicitly warn the user.
Phase 6: Synthesis – Answer with Full Traceability
3.11 Conflict Resolution (synthesis/conflict_resolver.py)
Check for contradictions among the top chunks. Use an LLM to compare claims
(e.g., two chunks giving different dosage advice).
If contradictions exist, group them into a Contradiction Cluster.
Weight the authority_score: if a 1.0 FDA source contradicts a 0.3 blog, the
resolver sides with 1.0 but exposes the disagreement in the final answer.
Also, overlay patient_context: if a chunk recommends an NSAID but the
patient has Hypertension, flag a patient_specific_contraindication using
the conditions/medications list. This implements the logic from page 9 of the
inference document.
3.12 Response Builder (synthesis/response_builder.py)
Final LLM call: Prompt includes the original query, the reconciled top chunks,
any contradictions, and any knowledge graph overrides.
Instructions:
Ground every claim in the retrieved chunks (citation markers like [1], [2]).
If contradictions exist, acknowledge them: “Some sources suggest X, while others
recommend Y.”
If a drug interaction is found by kg_overrides, place a bold warning: “⚠️
Based on your current medication, Ibuprofen may interact with Lisinopril.
Consult your doctor before taking it.”
Always include a disclaimer.
Citation resolution: The LLM outputs reference IDs (like [1]). The builder must
map these back to the document metadata. This is where PostgreSQL is queried:
For each chunk cited, use the doc_uid from Neo4j to query PostgreSQL for
title, source, authority_score.
Attach the full citation block to the response, as per the API contract (page 7 of
inference document).
Phase 7: Evaluation Framework
From Evaluation.pdf and Stepwise approach.pdf, evaluation must be integrated
from day one.
3.13 Offline Evaluation Plan
Test datasets: MedQA, PubMedQA, MedMCQA + a custom internal test set of
200+ diverse queries (vague, multi-intent, emergency, etc.).
RAGAS Pipeline:
Measure faithfulness, answer relevance, context precision/recall, noise
ratio.
Run after every major change.
DeepEval / Grousee: Automatically assess fluency, toxicity, bias.
Human evaluation: Recruit 2-3 medical professionals (or students) to rate 100
responses on a rubric: clinical correctness, safety, clarity. Calculate
inter-annotator agreement.
Ablation studies: Turn off HYDE, multi-query, reflection loop one at a time and
report impact on accuracy and latency (as per Stepwise approach.pdf section
7).
3.14 Online Monitoring (Production KPIs)
Log every request/response tuple: query, strategy used, latency, confidence
score, final retrieved chunk IDs, user feedback (thumbs up/down).
Grounding rate: automated check using RAGAS faithfulness on a sample of
production traffic.
Alerts if grounding rate drops below 90% or hallucination spikes.
Bias & safety audit (every quarter): independent review of edge cases.
