5. Critical Design Decisions & Edge Cases
Latency budget: For medical use, aim for < 5 seconds end-to-end. Reflection
loop should only add one extra call, max two. If still low confidence, warn user
and suggest rephrasing the query.
When no retrieval is found: The chatbot must admit ignorance and not
hallucinate. “I couldn’t find enough information to answer that confidently.
Please consult a healthcare professional.”
Patient context updates: The frontend is responsible for passing up-to-date
medications. The inference service does not fetch patient history from the
knowledge graph because the document states “patient data … will be provided
by the front end”. This is a design contract.
Citation integrity: The doc_uid from Neo4j is the link. Make sure your pipeline
ensures that doc_uid in Neo4j exactly matches the PostgreSQL doc_uid
column. None should be missing.
Fallback embeddings: If the primary BioLORD model is unavailable, downgrade
to a generic medical embedding model (like PubmedBERT) with a 768-dim
projection. Plan this into neo4j_search.py.
6. Conclusion
The described implementation strategy transforms your existing pipeline into a fully
self-directed, safety-critical medical chatbot. By following the exact Self-RAG control
flow from your attached documents, using the right safety overrides (emergency guard,
kg_overrides, conflict resolution, and reflection), and embedding evaluation from day
one, you will build a system that is not only accurate but also provably safe and
auditable.
I recommend starting with a minimal viable RAG (intent guard + direct retrieval +
citations) to validate end-to-end connectivity, then incrementally layering the
intelligent strategies. This reduces risk and gives you a quick feedback loop.
